<SubSubSection title="Rolling on curved surfaces"  id="rolling_curved_surface">
    <p>
        When a circular rigid body rolls without slipping on a
        surface which is itself curved, the radius of curvature of
        the surface affects the acceleration (but not velocity) of
        points on the rolling body.
    </p>

    <RedText>INSERT INTERACTIVE BLOCK HERE</RedText>

    <DisplayEquation id="rko-eg" derivation='True' background="True" title="Geometric quantities for rolling on a curved surface." equation="\\begin{aligned} \\left.\\begin{aligned} R &amp;= \\rho - r \\\\ \\vec{\\omega} &amp;= -\\omega \\,\\hat{e}_b \\\\ \\vec{\\alpha} &amp;= -\\alpha \\,\\hat{e}_b \\end{aligned}\\right\\} &amp; \\text{ when rolling on the inside of a curved surface} \\\\[1em] \\left.\\begin{aligned} R &amp;= \\rho + r \\\\ \\vec{\\omega} &amp;= \\omega \\,\\hat{e}_b \\\\ \\vec{\\alpha} &amp;= \\alpha \\,\\hat{e}_b \\end{aligned}\\right\\} &amp; \\text{ when rolling on the outside of a curved surface} \\end{aligned}"> 
            These formulas are all choices of sign conventions for
            <InlineEquation equation="\\omega" /> and <InlineEquation equation="\\alpha" />, and definitions of <InlineEquation equation="R" />. Figure <a
            href="#rko-fc">#rko-fc</a> shows the appropriate
            geometry. Note that <InlineEquation equation="\\omega" /> and <InlineEquation equation="\\alpha" /> are defined
            with positive values corresponding to motion in the
            tangential direction.
    </DisplayEquation>

    <!-- WARNING -->
    <p>Warning: Radii of curvature <InlineEquation equation="\\rho" /> and
    <InlineEquation equation="R" /> may not be constant.</p>
    <p>
        The radius of curvature <InlineEquation equation="\\rho" /> of the surface may be
        varying with position as the body rolls. If <InlineEquation equation="\\rho" />
        changes then this will also cause <InlineEquation equation="R" /> to change. These
        two variables will only be constant if the surface is in
        fact perfectly circular.
      </p>
</SubSubSection>


